{"cursor":"3092","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'James Adam' (21 July 1732 – 20 October 1794) was a Scottish architect and\nfurniture designer, but was often overshadowed by his older brother and business\npartner, Robert Adam. They were sons of architect William Adam.\n\nIn 1755 James worked on Gunsgreen House in the Berwickshire town of\nEyemouth.\n\nIn 1758, Robert, James, and their younger brother William Adam started their\nbusiness in London (living in Lower Grosvenor Street), focusing on designing\ncomplete schemes for the decoration and furnishing of houses. Palladian design\nwas popular, but Robert had evolved a new, more flexible style incorporating\nelements of classic Roman design alongside influences from Greek, Byzantine and\nBaroque styles. The Adam brothersâ success can also be attributed to a desire to\ndesign everything down to the smallest detail, ensuring a sense of unity in\ntheir designs.\n\nHe then followed in Robert's footsteps by undertaking the [[Grand Tour]],\nleaving in May 1760 to October 1763, when he arrive back in London.\n\nJames succeeded Robert as Architect of the Kingâs Works in 1768 just before work\non the brothers' Adelphi project (1768â1772) almost bankrupted the firm (the\nbusiness employed other notable architects including Joseph Bonomi (1739â1808)\nwho, from 1768, remained with the Adams until 1781).\n\nFrom 1771-5 he was engaged with his brother in the design and building of\nWedderburn Castle near Duns, Berwickshire.\n\nJames emerged from his brother's shadow after Robert's death in 1792, designing\nseveral notable buildings in Glasgow, including the old Infirmary (1792;\ndemolished 1907), Assembly Rooms (1794; demolished in 1890) and the Tron Kirk\n(1794). He also designed Portland Place in central London. However, his glory\nwas short-lived — he died at his home in London's Albermarle Street in\nOctober 1794.\n\nDuring their lifetime Robert and James Adam published two volumes of their\ndesigns, Works in Architecture of Robert and James Adam (in 1773â1778 and 1779;\na third volume was published posthumously, in 1822).\n","linknr":115,"url":"James_Adam_(architect)","recorded":1375084557,"links":["/w/index.php?title=James_Adam_(architect)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=James_Adam_(architect)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Gunsgreen_House,_Eyemouth.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Gunsgreen_House%2C_Eyemouth.jpg/220px-Gunsgreen_House%2C_Eyemouth.jpg","/wiki/File:Gunsgreen_House,_Eyemouth.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf11/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Scotland","/wiki/Architect","/wiki/Furniture_designer","/wiki/Robert_Adam","/wiki/William_Adam_(architect)","/w/index.php?title=Gunsgreen_House&action=edit&redlink=1","/wiki/Eyemouth","#cite_note-1","/w/index.php?title=William_Adam_(Jr)&action=edit&redlink=1","/wiki/London","/wiki/Roman_architecture","/wiki/Architecture_of_Ancient_Greece","/wiki/Byzantine_architecture","/wiki/Baroque","/wiki/Grand_Tour","/wiki/Office_of_Works","/wiki/Adelphi,_London","/wiki/Joseph_Bonomi_the_Elder","/wiki/Wedderburn_Castle","/wiki/Duns","/wiki/Berwickshire","/wiki/Glasgow","/wiki/Portla